<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="410" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,616,151,213]" box="[151,368,187,213]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
<figureCitation box="[151,286,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Figs. 29–33</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[297,368,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–76" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[223,1363,184,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-16@7.[223,1363,181,1799]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 63–76. 63―paratype of M. bogutensis, style, 64―same, male from the type locality, 65―same, drawing from the original description (after Mityaev, 1990), 66–68―same, males from Dzhungarskiy Alatau (M. zhuravlevi sensu Mityaev, 2014), 69―same, drawing from the original description of M. zhuravlevi (after Mityaev, 2014), 70―M. kajkanus, penis, back view, 71―same, frontal and lateral view, 72―same, lateral view, 73―distribution map of species of the M. bogutensis group, 74–76―biotopes,where insects were collected; localities, where photos were taken are shown with arrows, the whitish green plant in the center of each photo is Artemisia (Seriphidium) juncea." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">70–72</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,1258]" box="[151,1306,259,286]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,259,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Description.</emphasis>
In appearance and coloration, indistinguishable from most other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ribaut" authorityYear="1952" box="[1146,1299,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1146,1299,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Macropsidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
Aedeagus in posterior view with narrow lateral carinae slightly not reaching gonopore (
<figureCitation box="[1177,1262,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–76" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[223,1363,184,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-16@7.[223,1363,181,1799]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 63–76. 63―paratype of M. bogutensis, style, 64―same, male from the type locality, 65―same, drawing from the original description (after Mityaev, 1990), 66–68―same, males from Dzhungarskiy Alatau (M. zhuravlevi sensu Mityaev, 2014), 69―same, drawing from the original description of M. zhuravlevi (after Mityaev, 2014), 70―M. kajkanus, penis, back view, 71―same, frontal and lateral view, 72―same, lateral view, 73―distribution map of species of the M. bogutensis group, 74–76―biotopes,where insects were collected; localities, where photos were taken are shown with arrows, the whitish green plant in the center of each photo is Artemisia (Seriphidium) juncea." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Fig. 70</figureCitation>
). Ventral carina with evenly curved margin, runs all along shaft from base to gonopore (
<figureCitation box="[953,1091,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–76" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[223,1363,184,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-16@7.[223,1363,181,1799]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 63–76. 63―paratype of M. bogutensis, style, 64―same, male from the type locality, 65―same, drawing from the original description (after Mityaev, 1990), 66–68―same, males from Dzhungarskiy Alatau (M. zhuravlevi sensu Mityaev, 2014), 69―same, drawing from the original description of M. zhuravlevi (after Mityaev, 2014), 70―M. kajkanus, penis, back view, 71―same, frontal and lateral view, 72―same, lateral view, 73―distribution map of species of the M. bogutensis group, 74–76―biotopes,where insects were collected; localities, where photos were taken are shown with arrows, the whitish green plant in the center of each photo is Artemisia (Seriphidium) juncea." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Figs. 71–72</figureCitation>
). Aedeagal apex somewhat expanded, with only 1–3 if any blunt denticles on each side. Shape of pygofer appendages and styles same as in most other members of genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="410" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,439,465]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Hosts.</emphasis>
Originally collected from undetermined species of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Mityaev, 1990)" baseAuthorityName="Mityaev" baseAuthorityYear="1990" box="[869,1173,439,465]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[869,978,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Artemisia</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mityaev, I. D." box="[995,1165,439,465]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" pagination="5 - 20" refId="ref4762" refString="Mityaev, I. D. (1990) New Auchenorrhyncha from mountain landscapes of Kazakhstan. Trudy Instituta Zoologii Akademii Nauk Kazakhskoy SSR, 45, 5 - 20. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1990">Mityaev, 1990</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; later 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="juncea" subGenus="Seriphidium">
<emphasis box="[1247,1271,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1290,1427,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Seriphidium</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[151,226,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">juncea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recorded as a host plant for specimens from the 
<typeStatus box="[832,880,476,502]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">type</typeStatus>
series (
<bibRefCitation author="Mityaev, I. D." box="[968,1137,475,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" pagination="1 - 170" refId="ref4797" refString="Mityaev, I. D. (2002) Fauna, ecology, and zoogeography of leafhoppers (Homoptera, Cicadinea) of Kazakhstan. Tethys Entomological Research, 5, 1 - 170. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="2002">Mityaev, 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens for this study were collected from 
<taxonomicName box="[382,651,511,537]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="juncea" subGenus="Seriphidium">
<emphasis box="[382,406,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[422,559,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Seriphidium</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[576,651,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">juncea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
growing on stony slopes (
<figureCitation box="[946,1030,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–76" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[223,1363,184,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-16@7.[223,1363,181,1799]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 63–76. 63―paratype of M. bogutensis, style, 64―same, male from the type locality, 65―same, drawing from the original description (after Mityaev, 1990), 66–68―same, males from Dzhungarskiy Alatau (M. zhuravlevi sensu Mityaev, 2014), 69―same, drawing from the original description of M. zhuravlevi (after Mityaev, 2014), 70―M. kajkanus, penis, back view, 71―same, frontal and lateral view, 72―same, lateral view, 73―distribution map of species of the M. bogutensis group, 74–76―biotopes,where insects were collected; localities, where photos were taken are shown with arrows, the whitish green plant in the center of each photo is Artemisia (Seriphidium) juncea." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Fig. 76</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,547,573]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Calling signal.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation collectingDate="2017-06-19" country="Kazakhstan" county="Kolbay Village" latitude="45.7" location="Signals" longLatPrecision="67" longitude="80.297" municipality="Lepsy River" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" specimenCount="1" specimenCount-male="1">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03BF87A7C406FF9CC9846EB9CA9CB49B:8EC9606AC406FF9CC8926C0DCF81B24C" box="[385,467,547,573]" country="Kazakhstan" county="Kolbay Village" latitude="45.7" longLatPrecision="67" longitude="80.297" municipality="Lepsy River" name="Signals" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Signals</location>
of 
<specimenCount box="[512,617,547,574]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" type="male">one male</specimenCount>
from 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03BF87A7C406FF9CC9846EB9CA9CB49B:8EC9606AC406FF9CCBA66C0DCD14B24C" box="[693,838,547,573]" country="Kazakhstan" county="Kolbay Village" latitude="45.7" longLatPrecision="67" longitude="80.297" municipality="Lepsy River" name="Southeastern" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Southeastern</location>
<collectingCountry box="[848,979,547,573]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
(foothills of 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03BF87A7C406FF9CC9846EB9CA9CB49B:8EC9606AC406FF9CCD626C0DCB30B24C" box="[1137,1378,547,573]" country="Kazakhstan" county="Kolbay Village" latitude="45.7" longLatPrecision="67" longitude="80.297" municipality="Lepsy River" name="Dzhungarskiy Alatau" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Dzhungarskiy Alatau</location>
near the gorge of the 
<collectingMunicipality box="[336,474,583,610]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Lepsy River</collectingMunicipality>
at its exit from the mountains to the plain, 
<quantity box="[962,1034,583,609]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" unit="km" value="13.0">13 km</quantity>
south of 
<collectingCounty box="[1140,1313,583,609]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Kolbay Village</collectingCounty>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1324,1432,583,610]" degrees="45.700" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" precision="55" value="45.7">45.700 N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[151,254,619,646]" degrees="80.297" direction="east" orientation="longitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" precision="55" value="80.297">80.297 E</geoCoordinate>
, from 
<taxonomicName box="[328,596,619,645]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="juncea" subGenus="Seriphidium">
<emphasis box="[328,352,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[368,505,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Seriphidium</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[521,596,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">juncea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<date box="[610,753,619,646]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" value="2017-06-19">
<collectingDate box="[610,753,619,646]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" value="2017-06-19">19. VI. 2017</collectingDate>
</date>
) were recorded at 29 
<superScript attach="left" box="[989,997,619,633]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">o</superScript>
C
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
Male calling signal is a phrase lasting for 5–10 s in the recordings and consisting of syllables following each other with a period from 0.3– 
<geoCoordinate box="[482,535,691,718]" degrees="0.4" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" precision="5555" value="-0.4">0.4 s</geoCoordinate>
at the beginning to 0.8– 
<geoCoordinate box="[808,861,691,718]" degrees="0.9" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" precision="5555" value="-0.9">0.9 s</geoCoordinate>
(occasionally, up to 1 s and more) at the end (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Figs. 29–31</figureCitation>
). Each syllable includes the low-amplitude rather variable initial part and the high-amplitude component consisting of 6–10 partially merged pulses (
<figureCitation box="[644,783,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Figs. 32–33</figureCitation>
). Often, low-amplitude parts of syllables gradually reduce towards the end of a phrase, so that the end syllables in a phrase sometimes consist of only high-amplitude component (
<figureCitation box="[215,299,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
On the whole, in temporal pattern, the calling signal of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mityaev" authorityYear="1990" box="[815,952,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kajkanus">
<emphasis box="[815,952,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">M. kajkanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Mityaev" authorityYear="2014" box="[1174,1331,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bogutensis">
<emphasis box="[1174,1331,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">M. bogutensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Syllable repetition period ranges in these species considerably overlap, and syllables share similar final component consisting of several partially merged pulses (
<figureCitation box="[586,849,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Figs. 26–28 and 32–33</figureCitation>
). Since the initial low-amplitude part of a syllable in both species is variable, occasionally, some syllables in phrases of two species are almost indistinguishable (two last syllables on 
<figureCitation box="[291,371,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
and on 
<figureCitation box="[460,543,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="410" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1051,1077]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Distribution.</emphasis>
All known records are restricted to the arid foothills of the eastern part of Dzhungarskiy Alatau, Southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[303,434,1087,1113]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[449,533,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–76" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[223,1363,184,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-16@7.[223,1363,181,1799]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 63–76. 63―paratype of M. bogutensis, style, 64―same, male from the type locality, 65―same, drawing from the original description (after Mityaev, 1990), 66–68―same, males from Dzhungarskiy Alatau (M. zhuravlevi sensu Mityaev, 2014), 69―same, drawing from the original description of M. zhuravlevi (after Mityaev, 2014), 70―M. kajkanus, penis, back view, 71―same, frontal and lateral view, 72―same, lateral view, 73―distribution map of species of the M. bogutensis group, 74–76―biotopes,where insects were collected; localities, where photos were taken are shown with arrows, the whitish green plant in the center of each photo is Artemisia (Seriphidium) juncea." pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="410" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,259,1258]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,1123,1149]" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Remark.</emphasis>
In appearance and genitalia shape, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mityaev" authorityYear="1990" box="[695,831,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kajkanus">
<emphasis box="[695,831,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">M. kajkanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlabola" authorityYear="1963" box="[1026,1162,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valiturus">
<emphasis box="[1026,1162,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">M. valiturus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Tishechkin, 2014)" baseAuthorityName="Tishechkin" baseAuthorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="araxes">
<emphasis box="[1214,1325,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">M. araxes</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Tishechkin, D. Yu." pageId="5" pageNumber="410" pagination="155 - 167" refId="ref5364" refString="Tishechkin, D. Yu. (2014) Review of species of the genus Macropsidius Ribaut, 1952 (Homoptera: Cicadellidae: Macropsinae) of Russia and adjacent territories. Russian Entomological Journal, 23 (3), 155 - 167. Available from: http: // kmkjournals. com / upload / PDF / REJ / 23 / ent 23 _ 3 _ 155 _ 167 _ Tishechkin. pdf (accessed 5 February 2022) https: // doi. org / 10.15298 / rusentj. 23.3.01" type="journal article" year="2014">Tishechkin, 2014</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. However, these two species are known only from Caucasus, Transcaucasia, and the adjacent regions of 
<collectingCountry box="[151,199,1196,1222]" name="Iran" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">Iran</collectingCountry>
, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mityaev" authorityYear="1990" box="[310,448,1195,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kajkanus">
<emphasis box="[310,448,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="410">M. kajkanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was never found outside the eastern part of Dzhungarskiy Alatau. For this reason, their synonymization without comprehensive investigation of Caucasian species would be premature.
</paragraph>
